{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598192"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15446"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.1,0.03,0.23,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8137"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8137"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48212"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20442"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EColonic diverticular disease is a common condition in Western populations and its prevalence increases with age.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about diverticular disease is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The exact mechanism of diverticula formation is clearly understood","Diverticula contain only mucosal layer herniation","Diverticulitis has no infectious component","Bleeding and perforation often occur simultaneously","Bleeding can often be a complication requiring treatment"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EColonic diverticular disease is characterised by herniation of mucosa and submucosa through the muscular wall of the colon. \u003Cstrong\u003EThe exact mechanism\u003C/strong\u003E of diverticula formation remains incompletely understood, though factors such as increased intraluminal pressure, altered colonic motility, and weakening of the colonic wall likely contribute. The condition is seen most often in Western communities and is relatively uncommon in developing communities. It is thought that the main reason for this is the dietary differences, where the diet in Western populations is relatively low in fibre, but genetic differences are also apparent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticula\u003C/strong\u003E consist of both mucosal and submucosal layers herniating through the muscular layer, typically at points where blood vessels penetrate the colonic wall. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when these outpouchings become infected and inflamed, often due to micro-perforation or faecal stasis. While conservative management is often successful, endoscopic or surgical interventions may be required where there is bleeding or an acute inflammatory episode. Bleeding and perforation have rather different pathological process and do not often occur simultaneously. \u003Cstrong\u003EBleeding\u003C/strong\u003E from diverticular disease can be significant and may require urgent intervention including endoscopic treatment, angiographic embolisation, or surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diverticula are outpouchings of mucosa and submucosa through the muscular wall of the colon","The exact mechanism of diverticular formation remains incompletely understood","Diverticulitis occurs when diverticula become inflamed and infected","Complications of diverticular disease include bleeding, perforation, and abscess formation"],"references":["Piscopo N, Ellul P. Diverticular Disease: A Review on Pathophysiology and Recent Evidence. Ulster Med J. 2020 Sep;89(2):83-88. Epub 2020 Oct 21. PMID: 33093692; PMCID: PMC7576390.","Linzay CD, Pandit S. Acute Diverticulitis. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29083630.","Talutis SD, Kuhnen FAH. Pathophysiology and Epidemiology of Diverticular Disease. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2021 Mar;34(2):81-85. doi: 10.1055/s-0040-1716698. Epub 2020 Dec 8. PMID: 33642946; PMCID: PMC7904337.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Williams S, Bjarnason I, Hayee B, et al. Diverticular disease: update on pathophysiology, classification and\u00a0management. Frontline Gastroenterology 2024; 15:50\u201358."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48212"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15446"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48212"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T18:33:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-18T18:34:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8137"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}}